      <body>
         <div type="ReferencedPersons">
            <listPerson sortKey="ReferencedPersons">
               <person xml:id="MA_Gaskell_Holland">
                  <persName ref="#MA_Gaskell_Holland">
                     <surname type="paternal">Gaskell</surname>
                     <surname type="married">Holland</surname>
                     <forename>Marianne</forename>
                     <addName>MA</addName>
                  </persName>
                  <birth>
                     <date when="1834-09-12">September 12 1834</date><placeName ref="#Manchester">Manchester, UK</placeName>/>
                  </birth>
                  <death>
                     <date when="1920"></date>
                     <placeName ref="#Manchester"/>
                  </death>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>The Gaskells’ first surviving daughter, born <date when="1834-09-12">September 12, 1834</date>. Marianne is the subject of most of the diary, and is described as <q>gentle</q>. She was the only one of Gaskell’s daughters to become a mother herself, though she was still unmarried at the time of Gaskell’s death.</p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Wm_Gaskell">
                  <persName ref="#Wm_Gaskell">
                     <surname>Gaskell</surname>
                     <forename>William</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <birth><date when="1805-07-24">July 24, 1805</date>
                     <placeName ref="#Latchford">Latchford, Warrington, UK</placeName>
                  </birth>
                  <death when="1884-06-11">
                     <placeName ref="#Manchester">Manchester, UK</placeName>
                  </death>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>Elizabeth Gaskell’s husband, a Unitarian minister. They married August 30, 1832. At the time, William was serving at the Cross Street Chapel, Manchester, with J. G. Robberds.
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Madame_deSaussure">
                  <persName ref="#Mme_DeSaussure">
                     <surname>de Saussure</surname>
                     <surname>Necker</surname>
                     <forename>Albertine</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <birth when="1766">
                     <placeName ref="#Geneva"/>
                  </birth>
                  <death when="1841">
                     <placeName ref="#Geneva"/>
                  </death>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>Mme Necker de Saussure was a Swiss woman of letters, most well known for her <q>L’Education progressive</q>. She was related through her botanist husband to Germaine de Staël.</p>
                 </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Andrew_Combe">
                  <persName ref="#Andrew_Combe">
                     <surname>Combe</surname>
                     <forename>Andrew</forename>
                     <roleName>Physician</roleName>
                  </persName>
                  <birth when="1797-10-27">
                     <placeName ref="#Edinburgh"></placeName>
                  </birth>
                  <death when="1847-08-09">
                     <placeName ref="#Edinburgh"/>
                  </death>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk"><p>Author, scientist. Combe was a Physician/Phrenologist, who established the <title>Phrenological Journal</title> with his brother and others. He was also the President of <orgName>Edinburgh Phrenological Society</orgName> in 1827. Gaskell quotes his <title><hi rend="italics">Physiology applied to Health and Education</hi></title> (1834), which was a bestseller.
                  </p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Betsy_household">
                  <persName ref="#Betsy_household">
                     <surname>Unknown</surname>
                     <forename>Betsy</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>Betsy was a servant of the Gaskells, who also appears to have worked as a nurse to the children. She is mentioned early on in the journal in several entries. Shortly after the birth of Meta (Margaret Emily, the Gaskells' second surviving daughter), she was replaced by Elizabeth.</p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Margaret_Gaskell_Dimock">
                  <persName ref="#Margaret_Gaskell_Dimock">
                     <surname type="married">Dimock</surname>
                     <surname type="married">Gaskell</surname>
                     <surname type="maiden">Jackson</surname>
                     <forename>Margaret</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <death when="1850-01-12">January 12, 1850, aged 69 years. <!-- Chapple, Early Years p. 403 -->
                     <placeName ref="#Warrington"/>
                  </death>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk"><p>Margaret Gaskell, later Dimock, was William Gaskell&#39;s mother. William (b. 1805) was the oldest of five children: including Samuel (1807), Anne (1808), Margaret (b. 1810, died 1816), Elizabeth (1812), Robert (1814) and John (b. 1816, died 1821). After her first husband's death in 1819, she married Rev. Edward Dimock, who had arrived as the Pastor of Sankey Street Chapel in 1822.</p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Fanny_household">
                  <persName ref="#Fanny_household">
                     <surname>Unknown</surname>
                     <forename>Fanny</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>A servant, mentioned in the diary. No other information is known about Fanny.</p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Elizabeth_Stevenson_Gaskell">
                  <persName ref="#Elizabeth_Stevenson_Gaskell">
                     <surname type="married">Gaskell</surname>
                     <surname type="maiden">Stevenson</surname>
                     <forename>Elizabeth</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <birth when="1810-09-29">
                     <placeName ref="#Chelsea">"Bell Vue, Chelsea"</placeName>
                  </birth>
                  <death when="1865-11-12">
                     <placeName ref="#Alton"></placeName>
                  </death>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>Elizabeth Gaskell, the author of the journal, was born in 1810 and died in 1865. She published her first novel, <hi rend="italic">Mary Barton</hi>, in 1848, and later became a successful novelist.</p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Hannah_Holland_Lumb">
                  <persName ref="#Hannah_Holland_Lumb">
                     <surname type="married">Lumb</surname>
                     <surname type="maiden">Holland</surname>
                     <forename>Hannah</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <birth when="1767-07-29">
                     <placeName ref="#Knutsford"></placeName>
                  </birth>
                  <death when="1837-05-01">
                     <placeName ref="#Knutsford"></placeName>
                  </death>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>Elizabeth Gaskell’s mother’s sister, who nursed her during her final illness. After Elizabeth Stevenson’s death, Hannah Lumb and her daughter, Marianne, took Gaskell to live with them in Knutsford. Marianne died shortly after, and Gaskell lived with Aunt Lumb until her marrriage. 
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Mrs_Collins">
                  <persName ref="#Mrs_Collins">
                     <surname>Collins</surname>
                    
                  </persName>
                 
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>Neighbor of the Gaskells'. No other information known.</p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Richard_Deane">
                  <persName ref="#Richard_Deane">
                     <surname>Deane</surname>
                     <roleName>Physician</roleName>
                     <forename>Richard</forename>
                  </persName>
                  
                  <death when="1851-01-20"></death>

                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>Dr. Richard Thomas Deane, business partner of EG’s oldest uncle, Dr. Peter Holland, of Church House in Knutsford. After his first wife died, he married Susan Holland (1811-1889), Peter Holland’s daughter and Elizabeth Gaskell’s cousin. </p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="MaryAnn_Deane">
                  <persName ref="#MaryAnn_Deane">
                     <surname type="married">Deane</surname>
                     <surname/>
                     <forename>Mary Ann</forename>
                  </persName>
                 
                  <death when="1842-03-30">
                     </death>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>Mary Ann Deane, first wife of Dr. Richard Deane. Edward and Emily were two of their children.</p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Emily_Deane">
                  <persName ref="#Emily_Deane">
                     <surname>Deane</surname>
                     <forename>Emily</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <birth when="1835"></birth>
                  <!--Still living 1861, death unknown -->
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>Daughter of Dr. and Mrs. Deane of Knutsford</p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Anne_Gaskell">
                  <persName ref="#Anne_Gaskell">
                     <surname type="married">Robson</surname>
                     <surname type="maiden">Gaskell</surname>
                     <forename>Anne</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <birth when="1808">
                     <placeName ref="#Warrington"></placeName>
                  </birth>
                
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p></p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Meta_Gaskell">
                  <persName ref="#Meta_Gaskell">
                     <surname>Gaskell</surname>
                     <forename>Margaret Emily</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <birth when="1837-02-05">
                     <placeName ref="#Manchester"/>
                  </birth>
                  <death when="1913-10-26">
                     <placeName ref="#Manchester"/>
                  </death>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>The Gaskells’ second surviving daughter, Margaret Emily, called “Meta”, was born on Feburay 5, 1837. The diary describes Meta as clever and lively. </p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Bessy_Holland">
                  <persName ref="#Bessey_Holland">
                     <surname type="married">Howorth</surname>
                     <surname type="maiden">Holland</surname>
                     <forename>Bessy</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <birth when="1796-02-22">
                     <placeName ref="#Knutsford"></placeName>
                  </birth>
                  <death when="1886-07-16">
                   
                  </death>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>A cousin of Gaskell’s, Bessy was the daughter of Dr. Peter Holland, the ?oldest son of Gaskell’s grandfather, Samuel Holland, of Sandlebridge in Knutsford. Bessy was a friend of Maria Edgeworth. 
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Elizabeth_Barlow_household">
                  <persName ref="#Elizabeth_Barlow_household">
                     <surname>Barlow</surname>
                     <forename>Elizabeth</forename>
                  </persName>
                 
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>Elizabeth Barlowe who began working for the Gaskells in 1837, after Betsy left their service. Her name appears in the 1841 census records. No other information is known about her.</p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Elizabeth_Gaskell_Holland">
                  <persName ref="#Elizabeth_Gaskell_Holland">
                     <surname type="birth">Gaskell</surname>
                     <surname type="married">Holland</surname>
                     <forename>Elizabeth</forename>
                     <addName>Lizzy</addName>
                     <addName>Aunt Lizzy</addName>
                  </persName>
                  <birth when="1812">
                     <placeName ref="#Warrington"/>
                  </birth>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>William Gaskell's sister, Lizzy, was one of Gaskell's early correspondents. Most of the extant early letters are written to her. <!-- According to Dickens Journal site (see Zotero), Aunt Lizzy may have also written for household words. -->  </p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Abigail_Holland">
                  <persName ref="#Abigail_Holland">
                     <surname>Holland</surname>
                     <forename>Abigail</forename>
                     <addName>Aunt Ab</addName>
                  </persName>
                  <birth when="1773-09-12">
                     <placeName ref="#Knutsford"></placeName>
                  </birth>
                  <death when="1848-07-26"><placeName ref="#Knutsford"></placeName></death>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>An unmarried sister of Elizabeth Stevenson and Hannah Lumb, Abigail, “Aunt Ab”, lived with two of her brothers’ families (Swinton and Samuel) and taught their children before later moving to Heathside to live with Hannah and Elizabeth</p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Sam_Gaskell">
                  <persName ref="#Sam_Gaskell">
                     <surname>Gaskell</surname>
                     <roleName>Physician</roleName>
                     <forename>Samuel</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <birth when="1807">
                     <placeName ref="#Warrington"/>
                  </birth>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>William Gaskell’s brother and a doctor in Manchester. Sam had a particular affinity for patients with mental health problems, and eventually became superintendent of the Lancaster Asylum from 1840-1489, and was a member of the Luncacy Commission from 1849-1856.</p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="James_Partington">
                  <persName ref="#James_Partington">
                     <surname>Partington</surname>
                     <roleName>Physician</roleName>
                     <forename>James</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>James E. Partington, surgeon of Oxford Road, Manchester. Also looked after the family of J.G. Robberds.</p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Edward_Deane">
                  <persName ref="#Edward_Deane">
                     <surname>Deane</surname>
                     <addName>Eddy Deane</addName>
                     <forename>Edward</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <birth when="1833">
                     <placeName ref="#Knutsford"></placeName>
                  </birth>
                  <death when="1838">
                     <placeName ref="#Knutsford"></placeName>
                  </death>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>Son of Dr. and Mrs. Deane of Knutsford. His death of croup  at the age of 5 is recorded in the diary.
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </person>
            </listPerson>
         </div>
         <div type="NonReferencedHistoricalPersons">
            <listPerson sortKey="NonReferencedHistoricalPersons">
               <person xml:id="Florence_Gaskell_Crompton">
                  <persName ref="#Florence_Gaskell_Crompton">
                     <surname type="given">Gaskell</surname>
                     <surname type="married">Crompton</surname>
                     <forename>Florence</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <birth>
                     <date when="1842-10-07">October 7 1842</date>
                     <placeName ref="#Manchester"/>
                  </birth>
                  <death>
                     <date when="1881-10-05">October 5 1881</date>
                     <placeName ref="#London"/>
                  </death>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>The Gaskells’ third daughter (born 1842), who married Charles Crompton, and lived in London where she died aged 39. The couple had no children.</p>
                  </note>
               </person> <person xml:id="Julia_Gaskell">
                  <persName ref="#Julia_Gaskell">
                     <surname type="given">Gaskell</surname>
                     <surname/>
                     <forename>Julia</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <birth>
                     <date when="1845-09-03">September 3 1846</date>
                     <placeName ref="#Manchester"/>
                  </birth>
                  <death>
                     <date when="1908-10-24">October 24 1908</date>
                  </death>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>The Gaskells’ fourth daughter, (born 3 Sept. 1846 - 24 Oct. 1908). She, with her older sister Meta, remained unmarried and living in Knutsford, caring for their father after Gaskell’s death in 1865.</p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="William_Gaskell_son">
                  <persName ref="#William_Gaskell_son">
                     <surname>Gaskell</surname>
                     <surname/>
                     <forename>William</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <birth>
                     <date when="1844-10-23">Octover 23, 1844</date>
                     <placeName ref="#Manchester"/>
                  </birth>
                  <death when="1845-08-10">
                     <date when="1845-08-10">August 10, 1845</date>
                     <placeName ref="#Porthmadog">Porthmadog, UK</placeName>
                  </death>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>The Gaskells’ second born (first surviving) son,  who died in 1845 aged 9 months. An oft-cited anecdote recounts that Gaskell’s husband, also William, encouraged her to begin writing a novel to assist her in recovering from the grief of his death. The result was Mary Barton; his death is alluded to in the preface.
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="William_Stevenson">
                  <persName ref="#William_Stevenson">
                     <surname>Stevenson</surname>
                     <forename>William</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <birth when="1770">
                     <placeName ref="#Berwick"/>
                  </birth>
                  <death when="1828">
                  </death>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>Gaskell's Father</p>
                  </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="Elizabeth_Holland_Stevenson">
                  <persName ref="#Elizabeth_Holland_Stevenson">
                     <surname type="maiden">Holland</surname><surname/>
                     <surname type="married">Gaskell</surname>
                     <forename>Elizabeth</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <birth when="1771-04-19">
                     <placeName ref="#Knutsford"/>
                  </birth>
                  <death>
                     <date when="1811">October, 1811</date>
                     <placeName ref="#Chelsea"/>Chelsea, St. Luke <!-- Were living in a home in Beaufort Row, per Chapple p. 112 -->
                  </death>
                  <note type="bio" resp="#mjk">
                     <p>Gaskell’s mother, fourth daughter and sixth child of Samuel and Anne Holland of Sandlebridge, in Knutsford. Tradition, passed down through narratives of family and friends, holds that only her first (John) and last (Elizabeth) of 8 children survived, though only Elizabeth’s birth is registered. She died when Gaskell was 13 months old.</p>
                  </note></person>
               <person xml:id="John_Stevenson">
                  <persName ref="#John_Stevenson">
                     <surname type="given">Stevenson</surname>
                  <forename>John</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <birth when="1798-11-17">November 17 1798</birth>  
                  <death when="1828"></death>
               <note resp="mjk"><p>Gaskell’s older brother; a sailor, was lost at sea or in India sometime in fall 1828.</p></note> </person>
               <person xml:id="Catherine_Thompson_Stevenson">
                  <persName ref="#Catherine_Thompson_Stevenson">
                     <surname type="given">Thompson</surname>
                     <surname type="married">Stevenson</surname>
                     <forename>Catherine</forename>
                  </persName>
                  <birth when="1775">
                     <placeName ref="#Savannah">Savannah, Georgia</placeName>
                  </birth>
                  <death></death>
                  <note><p>Gaskell’s stepmother. Gaskell saw little of her father after the marriage. Catherine’s  brother married Katherine Byerly, who founded the school Gaskell attended.</p></note>
               </person>
               
            </listPerson>
         </div>
